INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '87136a1f-c358-49a4-bf0b-a62fa38b15c1',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Flutter — When to Bridge to Native (and How)$escape$,
  $escape$When building cross-platform Flutter apps, you might encounter scenarios where native functionality is required. This is where Platform Channels come into play. A Platform Channel is a bidirectional communication channel between your Flutter app and native code. To create a Platform Channel, you'll need to define a `MethodChannel` in your Flutter code and a corresponding `Platform` class in native code. For example, in Dart, you can create a `MethodChannel` like this:

```dart
import 'package:flutter/services.dart';

class MyPlatformChannel { static const platform = const MethodChannel('com.example.my_channel'); static Future<String> getPlatformVersion() async { final version = await platform.invokeMethod('getPlatformVersion'); return version; } }

```

In native code, you'll need to implement the `Platform` class with the required method, e.g., in Kotlin, it might look like this:

```kotlin
import io.flutter.embedding.engine.plugins.FlutterPlugin

class MyPlugin : FlutterPlugin {
 override fun onAttachedToEngine(binding: FlutterPluginBinding) {
 val channel = binding.engine.dartExecutor.binaryMessenger.channel
 channel.setMethodCallHandler { call, result ->
 when (call.method) {
 'getPlatformVersion' -> result.success('Android')
 else -> result.notImplemented()
 }
 }
 }
 override fun onDetachedFromEngine(binding: FlutterPluginBinding) {
 binding.engine.dartExecutor.binaryMessenger.channel.setMethodCallHandler(null)
 }
 }

```

This allows your Flutter app to invoke native code and receive results.$escape$,
  $escape$null$escape$,
  $escape$dart$escape$,
